	abstract = {Historically, the thalamus has been viewed as little more than a relay, simply transferring information
to key players of the cast, the cortex and hippocampus, without providing any unique functional
contribution. In recent years, evidence from multiple laboratories researching different thalamic
nuclei has contradicted this idea of the thalamus as a passive structure. Dated models of thalamic
functions are being pushed aside, revealing a greater and far more complex contribution of the
thalamus for cognition. In this Viewpoint, we show how recent data support novel views of thalamic
